#Text=Sigbrit Willoms
#Text=Sigbrit ( center ) and her daughter as Eilif Peterssen imagined them in 1876 .

#Text=Sigbrit Villoms ( also spelled Villums ) , [ 1 ] ( possible date of death 1532 ) , was a Danish-Norwegian politician from Amsterdam , mother to the mistress of King Christian II of Denmark , Dyveke Sigbritsdatter , and advisor and de facto minister of finance for the king between 1519 and 1523 . [ 2 ]
#Text=Biography
#Text=Sigbrit Willoms was born into a merchant family from Amsterdam .
#Text=One of her two brothers , Dionysius Villoms , is known to have been an apothecary .
#Text=She is known to have been educated in counting , reading and writing in the language Low German , and she is known to have been tutored in contemporary herbal medicine .
#Text=She belonged to one of the Dutch merchant families , that at this point in time entered into competition with the Germans , who had long dominated the trade in the Nordic countries .
#Text=At an unknown date , she moved to Bergen , Norway , where she is known to have lived in 1507 , in the company of her brothers .
#Text=She is known to have had a son , Reynold Sigbritssøn , who is otherwise not mentioned .

#Text=As none of her children are called illegitimate , Sigbrit Willoms must have been married , but her husband 's name is not mentioned anywhere , nor is it known when he died : he may have been named Nicolaas , and was most certainly dead by 1507 .
#Text=It is known that she did not use her husband 's name , as she used the patronymic Willoms or Villoms(datter ) .
#Text=She was the mother of Dyveke Sigbritsdatter , who met the future Danish King Christian II in Bergen in 1507 .
#Text=In this year , the close confidant of Crown Prince Christian , Erik Valkendorf , met them both at a stand in the market where they sold pastries .
#Text=The business of Sigbrit Willoms is not more closely mentioned , but it is noted that she still had a business company in Bergen in 1519 .
#Text=In 1507 , she is known to have kept an inn in Bergen , and to have sold pastries and vine on the market and in the harbor .
#Text=Valkendorf told the prince about Dyveke 's beauty , and the prince invited mother and daughter to a ball , after which Dyveke , with the consent of Sigbrit , became the lover of Christian .
#Text=Life in Denmark
#Text=In 1513 , when Christian became king of Denmark , mother and daughter moved with the king to Copenhagen .
#Text=Her brother , Dionysius Villoms , was named apothecary of the king , her other brother having been appointed to the office of lensmand at Bergenhus the year prior .
#Text=Her influence over the king became greater after the death of her daughter in 1517 , and she was made his political adviser and confidant .
#Text=From 1519 onward , she was accounted the most politically influential person in Denmark after the king himself .

#Text=In 1517 , Sigbrit was appointed to succeed her former antagonist Anne Meinstrup to the office of Hofmesterinde to the Queen 's Household , as well as put in charge of the Household of the Crown Prince Hans as royal governess .

#Text=The king put her in charge of the custom office and the royal treasury , in effect making her the de facto royal treasurer and Minister of Finance : she was however never formally called minister , but instead given the title of Mother Sigbrit , at that time normally an honorary title for the female head of a family .
#Text=Being a bourgeoise , she was known for forwarding the interests of the merchant classes and the interests of the cities in general .
#Text=In 1522 , she instigated a new law about hygiene in the capital city of Copenhagen , where people were told to have their houses cleaned every week .

#Text=She was unpopular with the nobility , and the target of public slander : because of her herbal knowledge , her critics spread rumors that she was a witch , and she was blamed for being the person behind the Stockholm Bloodbath in 1520 .
#Text=Later life and death
#Text=When King Christian was driven out of Denmark in 1523 , Sigbrit followed him to the Netherlands , where Christian asked for aid from his brother-in-law , the emperor .
#Text=The emperor made the condition that Christian was to get rid of Sigbrit , which Christian agreed to .
#Text=The date and circumstances of her death are unconfirmed .
#Text=In 1532 , a woman was detained in a prison in the Netherlands , who is believed to have been Sigbrit .
#Text=The emperor wished to have this prisoner executed for witchcraft .
#Text=It is not known if she was .
